From: experintellia <280144245+experintellia@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Thu, 9 Jul 2026 22:28:15 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 26/36] web-app: detect unreachable / CORS-blocked madmail
 server in webimap setup
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The webimap setup dialog handed off to onboarding as soon as the host
parsed, so a server that is down or (more commonly) a madmail server
without CORS enabled failed later inside the wasm core with an opaque
`fetch POST JsValue(TypeError: NetworkError when attempting to fetch
resource.)` alert — nothing the user could act on.

Pre-flight the parsed host before onboarding and disambiguate the two
causes a failed cross-origin fetch can't tell apart on its own: a normal
(cors) GET to <base>/ resolves only when the server sends an allowed
Access-Control-Allow-Origin; if that throws, a no-cors GET still resolves
whenever the server is merely reachable. cors-ok -> proceed; cors fails
but no-cors succeeds -> reachable but CORS-blocked; both fail ->
unreachable. Each case shows an actionable message instead of the opaque
core error, and the submit button shows a checking state.

The probe mirrors the core's base_url() scheme rule (http only for the
localhost/127.0.0.1/[::1] test hatch, https otherwise) so it targets the
same URL the account is created over, uses cache: 'no-store', and is only
a warning — submitting the same host again skips the probe and proceeds,
so a heuristic false positive is never a dead end.

Co-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
